          <h2 style="             
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;">What is the Phillips Curve?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.longandshort.com/email/images/what-is-the-phillips-curve.png" alt="An image of the floor of the New York Stock Exchange in 1964" href="https://www.longandshort.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            The floor of the New York Stock Exchange, 1964. Credits: fineartamerica.com
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000"> 
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">The <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #6b705c; color: black;" href="https://link.longandshort.com/ls-07-02-2025-f1-15-phillips-curve" target="_blank">Phillips Curve</a> is an economic concept that explains the relationship between <strong>unemployment and inflation</strong>. It theorizes that <strong>low unemployment</strong> results in <strong>higher inflation</strong>, while <strong>high unemployment</strong> leads to <strong>lower inflation</strong>.</p>
         <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">The logic behind the concept is that low unemployment results in businesses competing for human resources and paying <strong>higher wages</strong> to attract workers. The additional costs are passed on to consumers through higher prices, which results in inflation. High unemployment leads to <strong>stagnant wages</strong> keeping inflation low. The  Phillips curve is widely used by policymakers however its predictive power is still debated. Some economies argue that the Philips curve only holds true in the short term and loses its effectiveness in the long term.
         </p>
         <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"><strong>Example: US economy (Late 1960s)</strong>
         </p>
         <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">A classic example of the Phillips Curve is the US economy in the late 1960s. In 1965, <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #6b705c; color: black;" href="https://www.investopedia.com/historical-us-unemployment-rate-by-year-7495494" target="_blank">unemployment was at 4.0%</a>. As the economy expanded, it fell to 3.5% by 1969. This came at the cost of soaring inflation. As the government took measures to control inflation, unemployment rose dramatically to over 5% in the early 1970s.
         </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
